 additional benefits and pay information here:\nhttps://careers.microsoft.com/us/en/us-corporate-pay\n Microsoft will accept applications and processes offers for these roles on an ongoing basis.\n Responsibilities\n People Management\nModel: Embody company culture, values, and leadership principles in daily behavior.\nCoach: Set clear goals, support cross-functional success, and guide team learning.\nCare: Build strong teams by understanding individual aspirations and investing in their growth.\nDatacenter Operations\nGuide technicians on IT equipment handling, infrastructure interactions, and standard procedures.\nPromote ITIL practices and evaluate process changes to improve service quality and efficiency.\nEnsure policy compliance, resolve operational issues, and provide feedback to management.\nService Delivery\nCoordinate technician training and ensure access to tools and resources for task execution.\nInvestigate root causes of KPI-impacting issues and enforce quality checks and standards.\nValidate post-task compliance and collaborate with partners to correct design or deployment errors.\nManaging Service\nTrack and analyze team KPIs, share feedback, and drive performance improvements.\nManage escalations and collaborate with stakeholders to mitigate risks and ensure compliance.\nAssign and verify completion of training across technician roles and advise on certifications.\nDatacenter Work Environment\nLead safety briefings, ensure EHS compliance, and promote a proactive safety culture.\nEnforce physical security protocols and manage access violations and incident reporting.\nFoster team collaboration, share best practices, and monitor work impact across shifts.\nPhysical Requirements (Applies to but is not limited to US-based Data Center roles)\nOccasional climbing of ladders.\nFrequent climbing of stairs and/or ramps.\nProlonged standing.\nOccasional lifting 50lbs. / 22.5kg.\nOccasional push or pull 50-75lbs. / 22.5-34kg. with assistive device.\nNormal visual acuity (near, far and peripheral with correction).\nNormal color vision for electrical work.\nNormal is defined via standard medical terms and applicable criteria.\nLet me know if you'd like this formatted into a document or presentation slide.\nEmbody our culture and values.",
